   <tr>
      <td><center>Brian Humble - Lead Guitar and Vocals</center></td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
      <td><center><%= image_tag 'BrianinBurney.png' %></center></td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
      <td><p>Brian was about 12 years old in 1963 when popular music began a dramatic change with the likes of Chuck Berry,  Elvis, The Beatles, the Rolling Stone, Bob Dylan and Ray Charles to name just a few.  Watching these artists and others on the Ed Sullivan show was a revelation to him. That was the moment Brian knew he had to play the guitar and sing.   “I had been singing in the church choir and playing trombone in the school band, so I had the music basics and a family friend had given my older brother an old Kay F-hole acoustic guitar and that was the catalyst that I needed!”  Brian’s older brother, Scott taught him the basic on the guitar and the rest, as his mother would remind him, was just about practicing.  “I remember my very first song that I played on the guitar; it was The House of the Rising Sun, as done by the band the Animals. It was a great song to learn because it had more than the typical three chords of most  rock/blues songs.”  When Brian was asked why he began singing and playing the guitar, he replied, “to impress the girls, of course!  I once told a young lady that I played guitar and she responded...’who doesn’t’ “, sarcastically.</p>
          <p>“I ordered my first electric guitar from the Sears & Roebuck mail order catalog, and paid for it with my paper route earnings.  Wow, was I trilled when it finally arrived two weeks later.  Now, I had the electric guitar, but no amp to play it through”, Brian lamented.</p>
          <p>“I was very lucky to have wonderful music mentors in my life and supportive parents.  My high school band teacher, Bill Dwyer, was not only a great guitar player, but a wonderful person and friend.  I played in and organized many garage bands in my youth, my first band played in the corridor of the middle school for the lunch break.  My very first shot of performance adrenaline. We knew and  played only  two songs,’ For Your Love’ by the Yardbirds and ‘As Tears go by’, by the Stones.  I was hooked!  Fortunately, I lived in a small town and we could still have Saturday night dances in the school gym, or the local ‘slot car track’ or church social hall. So my high school band(s), in its many morphs, had plenty of venues to hone our sound and practice our craft.  Our peers had little choice, because we were one of the few, if not the only band in town!  Eventually, the serious players and I were able to put together a band that had some chops (including my music teacher Bill, my brothers Wick and Scott) and we played most weekends and summer at an upscale (in a rural kinda way) lodge, restaurant and lounge located in the country just  outside our little town,  during my last high school years and college summer breaks. “</p>
          <p>Brian reflected, “Wow, it has been great fun and I have met so many wonderful people and made many friends along the way.  I have played in pop bands, a brother band, country band, a band playing songs of the 30’s and 40’s, and now a retro rock band called Olde School, playing cover songs of the 50, 60 and 70’s! I am so glad I was inspired to learn to play the guitar!  Life is better when you embrace and perform music, it is truly the universal language.”</p>
      </td>
   </tr>
